// env_unix_timestamp — SELF-HOSTED `env.unix_timestamp()` over the WASI wall-clock floor
// (prim.clock_time_get), the v1 trust-spine realization of the effectful `env.unix_timestamp`.
// Returns the current Unix time in SECONDS (matching native `as_secs()`). It allocs an 8-byte
// scratch Bytes, fills it with the host clock value (nanoseconds) via prim.clock_time_get
// (clock_id 0 = CLOCK_REALTIME, precision 0), reads it as an i64, and divides by 1e9 to seconds.
// The scratch Bytes is a heap local dropped at scope end (no leak). Because this body reaches
// prim.clock_time_get, its cap_witness carries Capability::Clock — a DISTINCT capability (a
// clock read is neither a filesystem nor an entropy effect) — so a caller is caps-verified ONLY
// if it declares Clock (an `effect fn`); a pure `fn` reaching it is a frontend error AND would
// REJECT at the gate. A PLAIN `fn` (NOT `effect fn`, like random_int) so the bare i64 scalar
// return is not effect-monad/Result wrapped — `env.unix_timestamp` callers expect a raw Int.
// NON-DETERMINISTIC (reads the wall clock): no byte-match across runs.
fn env_unix_timestamp() -> Int = {
  let buf = prim.alloc_bytes(8)
  let p = prim.handle(buf) + 12
  let _e = prim.clock_time_get(0, 0, p)
  let ns = prim.load64(p)
  ns / 1000000000
}
